                            <header class="entry-header">
                                <h3 class="entry-title entry-title-small"><a href="https://jasons-indoor-guide-to-organic-and-hydroponics-gardening.com/blog/do-not-spray-weed-killer-on-wet-grass/" rel="bookmark">Why You Should Not Spray Weed Killer on Wet Grass</a></h3>                            </header>
                                                            <div class="entry-content">
                                    <p>It&#8217;s not a good idea to spray weed killer on wet grass. When the grass is wet, either from rain or morning dew, the weed killer can slide off the weeds and onto the surrounding grass or soil, making it less effective at targeting the weeds you&#8217;re trying to get rid of. Plus, it can lead to more of the chemical running off into areas where you don&#8217;t want it, like flower beds or lawns, which could harm the plants you want to keep. The time it takes for weeds to die after spraying with weed killer on dry grass &#8230;</p>
                                </div>
                                                        <span class="posted-on">Posted on <a href="https://jasons-indoor-guide-to-organic-and-hydroponics-gardening.com/blog/do-not-spray-weed-killer-on-wet-grass/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published updated" datetime="2024-05-05T16:58:46+00:00">May 5, 2024</time></a></span>                            <span class="byline"> by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://jasons-indoor-guide-to-organic-and-hydroponics-gardening.com/author/jason/">jason</a></span></span>                        </article>
                    </div>
